[_Klebsiella_ species, particularly _Klebsiella pneumoniae_ and _Klebsiella oxytoca_, are frequent nosocomial pathogens, especially among premature infants in neonatal intensive care units, causing pneumonia, urinary tract infections, septicemia, surgical wound sites, meningitis, and bacterial endophthalmitis (1-4). The presence of invasive devices such as IV catheters, endotracheal tubes, urinary catheters, and use of antibiotics are factors that increase the likelihood of nosocomial infection with _Klebsiella_ species. The primary pathogenic reservoirs for transmission are the gastrointestinal tract and the hands of hospital personnel. Klebsiella can spread rapidly, often leading to clonal nosocomial outbreaks, which may be caused by multidrug-resistant _Klebsiella_ spp, especially extended-spectrum-beta-lactamase (ESBL) or _K. pneumoniae_ carbapenemase (KPC) producers in neonatal wards. Often breaks in infection control practices are found to have facilitated nosocomial outbreaks.

1. Zakariya BP, Vishnu Bhat B, Harish BN, et al. Risk factors and outcome of _Klebsiella pneumoniae_ sepsis among newborns. Curr Pediatr Res 2012;16(2):115-118.
2. Fabbri G, Panico M, Dallolio L, et al. Outbreak of ampicillin/piperacillin-resistant _Klebsiella pneumoniae_ in a neonatal intensive care unit (NICU): investigation and control measures. Int J Environ Res Public Health 2013;10:808-815.
3. Morgan ME, Hart CA, Cooke RW. _Klebsiella_ infection in a neonatal intensive care unit: role of bacteriological surveillance. J Hosp Infect. 1984 Dec;5(4):377-85. Abstract available at: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6085092.
4. Gray J, Arvelo W, McCracken J, et al. An outbreak of _Klebsiella pneumoniae_ late-onset sepsis in a neonatal intensive care unit in Guatemala. Amer J Infect Control 2012; 40(6):516-520. Abstract available at: http://www.ajicjournal.org/article/S0196-6553(12)00711-0/abstract.
- Mod.ML

